diagnosis.2=The aggregate directional accuracy is not a clean one-number forecast capability signal for this kline benchmark.
diagnosis.3=Activity features are log1p-normalized and sign-trivial under the current expected.sign()==realized.sign() metric, producing directional_accuracy=1.0 while still carrying nontrivial MAE/RMSE.
diagnosis.4=The open coordinate is structurally suspect for direction scoring because the generator sets open to the previous close; after log-return normalization it behaves like a near-zero target, and the current forecast sign misses it on every valid sample.
diagnosis.5=Close-only directional accuracy is approximately coin-flip at 0.500254, so the MDN has not yet demonstrated phase-correct price-direction recovery on the protected range.
diagnosis.6=The next benchmark improvement should replace or supplement aggregate sign accuracy with feature-aware forecast metrics: close-return sign, price-delta/correlation/phase metrics, activity magnitude metrics, and causal baseline comparisons.
conclusion=Evidence/provenance is healthy for the forecast gate, but current metric semantics mix trivial activity signs with weak price-direction recovery. This is a forecast-semantics and model-quality diagnostic, not yet a policy-performance verdict.

