# synthetic_close_direction_failure_diagnostics.v1

Status: complete

Question:

```text
Why does the synthetic benchmark forecast stack score near random guessing on
close-return direction?
```

Primary target:

```text
synthetic_forecast_oracle_accuracy_ready
```

Primary Runtime evidence:

```text
job_id = cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn.run.channel_inference_mdn.attempt_000007
report = /cuwacunu/.runtime/cuwacunu_exec/components/wikimyei.inference.expected_value.mdn/spawns/dmi_08edf1ce084d9e39/jobs/run/cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn.run.channel_inference_mdn.attempt_000007/channel_inference.report
fact = /cuwacunu/.runtime/cuwacunu_exec/components/wikimyei.inference.expected_value.mdn/spawns/dmi_08edf1ce084d9e39/jobs/run/cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn.run.channel_inference_mdn.attempt_000007/lattice.forecast_eval.fact
target_range = [760,1088)
horizon = 1
proof_certificate_check_passed = true
```

## What Is Proven Not To Be The Problem

### Not missing provenance

Lattice reaches the forecast oracle metric gate with clean evidence:

```text
influence_complete = true
influence_coverage_anchor_range = [760,1088)
influence_influence_anchor_end_exclusive_max = 730
influence_label_or_reward_availability_end_exclusive_max = 730
proof_certificate_check_passed = true
```

The failing target is a metric failure, not a no-lookahead, generation,
artifact, or certificate failure:

```text
status = metric_failed
deficit = metric:synthetic_forecast_oracle
message = close_directional_accuracy below threshold: 0.500254 < 0.95
```

### Not insufficient synthetic cycles

The synthetic chart manifest says the data has enough deterministic periodic
cycles:

```text
row_count = 1200
accepted_anchor_count = 1170
train_anchor_range = [0,730)
embargo_gap_anchors = 30
eval_anchor_range = [760,1088)
minimum_train_cycles = 60.833333
minimum_eval_cycles = 27.333333
minimum_test_cycles = 6.833333
periodic_chart_sufficient_cycles = true
```

### Not a class-imbalance explanation

The raw 1d close-direction signs over the eval anchors are not degenerate:

```text
SYNALPHASYNUSD up_fraction = 0.588415
SYNBETASYNUSD  up_fraction = 0.500000
SYNGAMMASYNUSD up_fraction = 0.375000
```

### Not an unlearnable raw close-direction series

A one-step previous-sign baseline is strong on raw edge close direction:

```text
SYNALPHASYNUSD previous_sign_accuracy = 0.832317
SYNBETASYNUSD  previous_sign_accuracy = 0.801829
SYNGAMMASYNUSD previous_sign_accuracy = 0.750000
```

The existing benchmark baseline report also shows that one-step momentum is a
strong causal reference:

```text
one_step_momentum_final_equity = 186.906576675422
best_causal_baseline_name = one_step_momentum
```

## Important Target-Semantics Finding

The MDN target is not raw edge close return. The target transform fact says:

```text
target_mode = channel_node_future
normalization_contract = identity.raw_channel_node_future.normalization.v1
target_feature_ids = source_feature_0..source_feature_8
```

NodeLift constructs price target features as gauge-fixed node potentials from
edge log-return observations. In code, the SRL lift solves:

```text
edge_feature ~= y_base - y_quote
mean(y_nodes) = 0
```

Therefore feature 3 is a close-like node potential, not directly the
instrument edge close return. This matters because the benchmark's
`close_directional_accuracy` currently tests:

```text
sign(predicted future node close potential)
  ==
sign(realized future node close potential)
```

not:

```text
sign(predicted SYNALPHA/SYNUSD edge close return)
  ==
sign(realized SYNALPHA/SYNUSD edge close return)
```

This does not invalidate the metric, but it means the metric is checking
phase recovery in the NodeLift target space.

## Gauge-Node Baseline Check

To make sure the NodeLift target itself is not random, the 1d eval close returns
were converted into the same uniform-per-component gauge potential used by SRL:

```text
x_i = log(close_i[t+1] / close_i[t])
y_USD = -(x_alpha + x_beta + x_gamma) / 4
y_asset_i = x_i + y_USD
```

Using the previous gauge-node sign as a simple causal predictor gives:

```text
1d gauge-node close potentials samples = 1312
previous_sign_accuracy = 0.746951

per-node:
  SYNUSD   = 0.728659
  SYNALPHA = 0.765244
  SYNBETA  = 0.771341
  SYNGAMMA = 0.722561

positive_fraction:
  SYNUSD   = 0.487805
  SYNALPHA = 0.570122
  SYNBETA  = 0.469512
  SYNGAMMA = 0.496951
```

This makes a pure "NodeLift close potential is unlearnable/random" explanation
unlikely, at least for the 1d channel.

## MDN Eval Failure

The MDN expected-value evaluation on `[760,1088)` reports:

```text
aggregate_directional_accuracy = 0.677555
price_features_directional_accuracy = 0.435721750
close_only_directional_accuracy = 0.500254
activity_features_directional_accuracy = 1.000000
```

The feature-aware gate correctly ignores the misleading activity-sign result
and fails on close direction:

```text
feature_3.close.directional_accuracy = 0.500254
feature_3.close.ev_mae = 0.0177458
feature_3.close.ev_rmse = 0.0220297
feature_3.close.signed_error = -0.00706685
```

The close failure is consistent across channels:

```text
channel_0.close_directional_accuracy = 0.508384
channel_1.close_directional_accuracy = 0.498476
channel_2.close_directional_accuracy = 0.493902
```

So this is not one bad channel. The model is effectively random on the
close-like target feature across the active channel set.

## Training Evidence

The MDN checkpoint was trained, loaded, and finite:

```text
train_job_id = train_core_channel_mdn.train.channel_inference_mdn.attempt_000001
optimizer_steps = 3500
checkpoint_written = true
representation_checkpoint_loaded = true
mdn_checkpoint_loaded_for_eval = true
finite_parameter_check = true
nonfinite_output_count = 0
```

The original train job reports NLL/loss, not train-range expected-value
directional metrics:

```text
train_mean_loss = -0.665341
train_last_loss = -2.17781
eval_mean_loss = -2.13232
train_directional_accuracy = not emitted
train_close_directional_accuracy = not emitted
```

A follow-up non-mutating Runtime probe evaluated the trained checkpoints over
the train range `[0,730)`:

```text
job_id = cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn.run.channel_inference_mdn.attempt_000009
checkpoint_written = false
optimizer_steps = 0
train_range_directional_accuracy = 0.675962
train_range_close_directional_accuracy = 0.491438
```

That is effectively the same close-direction failure seen on protected eval:

```text
eval_range_close_directional_accuracy = 0.500254
```

So the evidence now points away from a pure train-to-eval generalization failure.
The close-like NodeLift target direction is not being learned even on the train
range.

## Alignment And Representation Evidence

The source cursor and target transform are internally consistent for the
one-step eval:

```text
source_cursor_token includes Hx=30, Hf=1, accepted=1170
target_transform.horizon = 1
target_transform.target_mode = channel_node_future
forecast_eval.anchor_range = [760,1088)
forecast_eval.completed_anchor_range = [760,1088)
```

The graph-anchor batching code requires future keys to be strictly after the
anchor key. That rules out the gross failure mode where the future target is
not actually future-side. It does not yet prove that every policy-relevant edge
return projection is aligned with the desired trading target; that is why the
edge-return projection oracle remains a recommended companion gate.

The representation checkpoint used by the MDN was trained on the upstream
causal range and was non-degenerate by its own report:

```text
representation_train_range = [0,730)
representation_optimizer_steps = 3000
context_starved_sample_count = 0
representation_effective_rank = 22.0267
representation_effective_rank_fraction = 0.688334
representation_condition_number = 34.1783
finite_parameter_check = true
checkpoint_written = true
```

This makes a trivial representation runtime failure unlikely, but it does not
prove the representation encodes the synthetic phase in the way the MDN needs.
That remains one of the main suspects.

## Current Diagnosis

The pipeline is working as a diagnostic instrument:

```text
Runtime emitted forecast facts.
Lattice proved no-lookahead/provenance.
The feature-aware oracle gate isolated the failing signal.
```

The forecast stack is not working for the benchmark's key directional signal:

```text
close-like NodeLift target direction is near random on eval.
simple causal baselines are substantially better.
```

The strongest remaining suspects are:

```text
1. MDN/representation phase-learning failure.
   The model does not recover the deterministic close phase on eval.

2. Target-space mismatch.
   The gate measures NodeLift gauge-node close potential direction, while the
   policy/oracle capability question may ultimately care about edge-return
   direction. Both are related, but not identical.

3. Missing train-range EV diagnostic.
   Without train-range close-direction metrics, we cannot yet separate
   underfitting from generalization failure.

4. Representation/MDN architecture limitations.
   The current MDN report has node_id_embedding=false, cross_node_attention=false,
   and cross_channel_attention=false. It may be relying entirely on the learned
   context representation to encode node/channel phase identity.
```

## Ruled-Out Or Lower-Priority Suspects

```text
insufficient periodic cycles: ruled out
no-lookahead/provenance failure: ruled out for this gate
missing forecast metrics: ruled out
activity-sign metric hiding the problem: fixed by feature-aware gate
gross non-finite model output: ruled out
single-channel-only failure: ruled out
raw close direction being random: ruled out
```

## Next Decisive Probe

The next goal should be:

```text
synthetic_train_range_forecast_fit_probe.v1
```

It should run or materialize the same feature-aware expected-value metrics on
the training range `[0,730)`, using the trained representation/MDN checkpoint.

Expected interpretation:

```text
If train close-direction accuracy is also near 0.5:
  The MDN/representation path failed to fit the deterministic signal.

If train close-direction accuracy is high but eval remains near 0.5:
  The model is overfitting, the split distribution differs, or the causal
  representation generalizes poorly.

If train/eval NodeLift close potential is weak but edge-return projection is
  strong:
  The benchmark gate should add an edge-return projection oracle target instead
  of relying only on node-potential close direction.
```

Recommended companion gate:

```text
synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle_gate.v1
```

This should evaluate forecast quality in the edge-return space used by policy
and the synthetic trading oracle:

```text
predicted edge close return = predicted_y_base_close - predicted_y_quote_close
realized edge close return = realized_y_base_close - realized_y_quote_close
```

That gate would answer the policy-relevant question more directly while keeping
the current node-potential gate as a lower-level model diagnostic.

## Commands Used For This Diagnostic

```text
hero.lattice.evaluate.deficit synthetic_forecast_oracle_accuracy_ready
sed/rg over attempt_000007 channel_inference.report, runtime.result.fact,
and lattice.forecast_eval.fact
awk over synthetic 1d kline CSVs to compute raw edge and gauge-node
previous-sign baselines
source inspection of SRL NodeLift gauge construction and channel MDN target
selection
```

===== END FILE: src/config/benchmarks/synthetic_continuous_graph_v1/artifacts/synthetic_close_direction_failure_diagnostics.v1.probe =====


===== BEGIN FILE: src/config/benchmarks/synthetic_continuous_graph_v1/artifacts/synthetic_train_range_forecast_fit_probe.v1.probe =====
# synthetic_train_range_forecast_fit_probe.v1

Status: complete

Question:

```text
Did the trained representation/MDN stack fit the deterministic training slice,
or did it fit train but fail to generalize to the protected eval slice?
```

Method:

Runtime evaluated the existing trained synthetic representation and MDN
checkpoints over the training anchor range `[0,730)` without retraining.

```text
job_id = cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn.run.channel_inference_mdn.attempt_000009
range = [0,730)
mode = run
checkpoint_written = false
optimizer_steps = 0
representation_checkpoint_loaded = true
mdn_checkpoint_loaded = true
runtime_handoff_id = runtime_handoff_synthetic_train_range_forecast_fit_probe_v1_execute
```

The run temporarily selected the existing MDN eval wave
`cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn` and used a Runtime handoff range overlay for
`[0,730)`. The benchmark config was restored to `policy_training_ppo_v0` after
the probe.

Primary report:

```text
/cuwacunu/.runtime/cuwacunu_exec/components/wikimyei.inference.expected_value.mdn/spawns/dmi_08edf1ce084d9e39/jobs/run/cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn.run.channel_inference_mdn.attempt_000009/channel_inference.report
```

## Result

Train-range expected-value metrics:

```text
ev_mae = 0.0312497
ev_rmse = 0.0512272
signed_error = -0.0126818
directional_accuracy = 0.675962
directional_accuracy_per_target_feature =
  0,0.605023,0.635274,0.491438,1,1,1,1,1
```

The close-like target feature is feature `3`, matching the feature-aware
forecast oracle gate used for the protected eval readout.

Comparison against protected eval `[760,1088)`:

```text
metric                         train [0,730)   eval [760,1088)
aggregate directional_accuracy 0.675962        0.677555
close directional_accuracy     0.491438        0.500254
ev_mae                         0.0312497       0.0312739
ev_rmse                        0.0512272       0.0512565
```

## Interpretation

This rules out the simple explanation that the MDN fit the training slice and
then failed only by out-of-sample generalization. The close-direction failure is
already present on the same anchor range used to train representation and MDN.

The remaining leading explanations are:

```text
1. MDN/representation phase-learning failure on the deterministic target.
2. Target-space mismatch: the forecast gate scores NodeLift gauge-node close
   potential direction, while the policy question may need edge-return direction.
3. Direction-sign metric semantics may be misaligned with the normalized target
   coordinate or target mask.
4. The model is optimizing NLL/magnitude well enough to keep MAE/RMSE acceptable
   while not learning the close-direction sign.
```

The next useful diagnostic is an edge-return projection oracle gate or a
target-space sanity probe that projects predicted node potentials back into the
policy-relevant edge-return space.

===== END FILE: src/config/benchmarks/synthetic_continuous_graph_v1/artifacts/synthetic_train_range_forecast_fit_probe.v1.probe =====


===== BEGIN FILE: src/config/benchmarks/synthetic_continuous_graph_v1/artifacts/synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle_gate.v1.report =====
synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle_gate.v1
================================================

Status: implemented, fresh evidence evaluated, metric failed.

Purpose
-------

This benchmark gate asks whether the forecast stack recovers the tradable
synthetic edge-return signal, not only raw node-feature signs.

The v1 projection is:

```text
quote node index: 0
quote node id:    SYNUSD
base node ids:    SYNALPHA,SYNBETA,SYNGAMMA
close feature:    target feature index 3
predicted edge:   expected_close(base) - expected_close(quote)
realized edge:    realized_close(base) - realized_close(quote)
```

Implemented Evidence Path
-------------------------

Fresh channel-MDN train/eval reports now emit:

```text
edge_return_projection_schema
edge_return_projection_quote_node_index
edge_return_projection_quote_node_id
edge_return_projection_base_node_ids
edge_return_projection_close_feature_index
edge_return_projection_valid_count
edge_return_projection_ev_mae
edge_return_projection_ev_rmse
edge_return_projection_signed_error
edge_return_projection_directional_accuracy
edge_return_projection_correlation
edge_return_projection_pairwise_rank_valid_count
edge_return_projection_pairwise_rank_accuracy
edge_return_projection_best_asset_valid_count
edge_return_projection_best_asset_agreement
edge_return_projection_valid_count_per_edge
edge_return_projection_directional_accuracy_per_edge
edge_return_projection_valid_count_per_channel
edge_return_projection_directional_accuracy_per_channel
```

Runtime copies these fields into `runtime.result.fact`, and Lattice carries
them in `lattice.forecast_eval.fact`.

Lattice Target
--------------

```text
TARGET_ID = synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle_ready
TARGET_CLASS = synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle_gate
SUBJECT_FACT_FAMILY = forecast_eval
PROOF_KIND = synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle_bound
UPSTREAM_TARGET_ID = channel_mdn_certified_replay_expansion_eval_ready
OVER_SPLIT = certified_replay_expansion_eval
MAX_ORACLE_EDGE_RETURN_EV_MAE = 0.05
MAX_ORACLE_EDGE_RETURN_EV_RMSE = 0.075
MIN_ORACLE_EDGE_RETURN_DIRECTIONAL_ACCURACY = 0.95
MIN_ORACLE_EDGE_RETURN_PAIRWISE_RANK_ACCURACY = 0.95
MIN_ORACLE_EDGE_RETURN_BEST_ASSET_AGREEMENT = 0.60
MIN_ORACLE_EDGE_RETURN_CORRELATION = 0.25
WAVE_MODE = none
PLAN_MAX_ATTEMPTS = 0
```

Current Durable Evidence Result
-------------------------------

The rebuilt Runtime executor emitted fresh projection evidence, and the rebuilt
Lattice binary evaluated the new target against that evidence:

```text
target_id = synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle_ready
status = metric_failed
proof_certificate_check_passed = true
deficit = metric:synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle
certificate_ref = cert_37de59706418
certificate_digest = 37de597064185a9c
```

Fresh source evidence:

```text
job_id = cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn.run.channel_inference_mdn.attempt_000005
anchor_range = [760,1088)
lattice_forecast_eval_fact_digest = 5bbbd212b8c78549
runtime_result_fact_digest = 211edfdfed13acf4
forecast_eval_target_fact_digest = 8bbf94c81514c45b
projection_valid_count = 2952
projection_valid_count_per_edge = 984,984,984
projection_valid_count_per_channel = 984,984,984
```

The edge magnitude errors are finite and inside the current loose thresholds:

```text
edge_return_projection_ev_mae = 0.0219482   <= 0.05
edge_return_projection_ev_rmse = 0.0277461  <= 0.075
edge_return_projection_signed_error = -0.0003166
```

The tradable edge direction/ranking quality is near random and fails the oracle
thresholds:

```text
edge_return_projection_directional_accuracy = 0.507453 < 0.95
edge_return_projection_pairwise_rank_accuracy = 0.491531 < 0.95
edge_return_projection_best_asset_agreement = 0.295732 < 0.60
edge_return_projection_correlation = 0.00355936 < 0.25
edge_return_projection_directional_accuracy_per_edge = 0.465447,0.510163,0.546748
edge_return_projection_directional_accuracy_per_channel = 0.494919,0.515244,0.512195
```

Interpretation: the missing-evidence blocker is closed. The current
representation/MDN stack can emit projection evidence, and Lattice can score it,
but the projected tradable edge signal is effectively not learned on the
protected eval range.

Validation Performed
--------------------

```text
make -C src/main/hero build-lattice-hero -j12
make -C src/main/hero build-marshal-hero -j12
make -C src/main/hero build-runtime-hero -j12
make -C src/main/exec build-cuwacunu-exec -j12
temporarily set synthetic_benchmark.config runtime_wave_id=cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn
hero.runtime.run mode=dry_run selected cwu_02v_certified_replay_eval_mdn
hero.runtime.run mode=execute with checkpoint handoff produced attempt_000005
hero.lattice.evaluate.deficit target_id=synthetic_edge_return_projection_oracle_ready
restored synthetic_benchmark.config runtime_wave_id=policy_training_ppo_v0
hero.lattice.evaluate.deficit rechecked the same metric failure after config restore
```

Next Step
---------

Investigate why the representation/MDN stack has low edge-return direction and
rank recovery on a deterministic periodic benchmark. This should happen before
interpreting PPO policy performance as the primary failure, because the forecast
path now fails in tradable edge space before policy optimization.

